        <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s13" slide="13" course="Math 2070" chapter="7" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=""><keywords slide="13" environ="slide" chapter="7" course="Math 2070"><keyword chapter="7" slide="13">Definition of a Ring</keyword><keyword chapter="7" slide="13"> ring</keyword><keyword chapter="7" slide="13">additive identity element</keyword><keyword chapter="7" slide="13">multiplicative identity element</keyword></keywords>
<xh:h3 xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">Definition of a Ring</xh:h3>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Definition" wbtag="defn" num="11" md5="0a206b94603b3aa73ff196bc390ebe06" course="Math 2070" chapter="7" slide="13" item="7.11">
A <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement"> ring</xh:b> $R$ (or $(R, +, \times)$) is a set equipped with two operations:
\[
\times, + : R\times R \rightarrow R
\]
which satisfy the following properties:
<xh:ol xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement">
<xh:li environment="statement"> Properties of $+$:
  <col_ol environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_ol">
  <col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
  Commutativity: $a + b = b + a$, $\forall a, b \in R$.
  </col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
  Associativity: $a + (b + c) = (a + b) + c$.
  </col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
  There is an element $0 \in R$ (called the <xh:b environment="col_ol">additive identity element</xh:b>),
  such that $a + 0 = a$ for all $a \in R$.
  </col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
  Every element of $R$ has an additive inverse; namely:
  For all $a \in R$, there exists an element of $R$, usually denoted $-a$,
  such that $a + (-a) = 0$.
  </col_li></col_ol>
</xh:li>
<xh:li environment="statement"> Properties of $\times$:
  <col_ol environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_ol">
  <col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
  Associativity: $a(bc) = (ab)c$.
  </col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
  There is an element $1 \in R$ (called the <xh:b environment="col_ol">multiplicative identity element</xh:b>),
  such that $1\times a = a\times 1 = a$ for all $a \in R$.
  </col_li></col_ol>
</xh:li>
<xh:li environment="statement"> Distributativity:
<col_ol environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_ol">
<col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
$a\times(b + c) = a\times b + a\times c$, for all $a, b, c \in R$.
</col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
$(a + b) \times c = a \times c + b\times c$, for all $a, b, c \in R$.
</col_li></col_ol>
</xh:li>
</xh:ol>
</statement>
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment=""/>
<xh:strong xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">Note:</xh:strong>
<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
<col_ol environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_ol">
<col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
For convenience's sake, we often write $ab$ for $a\times b$.
</col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
In the definition, commutativity is required of addition, but not of multiplication.
</col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
Every element has an additive inverse, but <xh:i xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ol"> not necessarily</xh:i> a multiplicative inverse.
That is, there may be an element $a \in R$ such that $ab \neq 1$ for all $b \in R$.
</col_li></col_ol>
</newcol>
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment=""/>
</slide>
        <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s14" slide="14" course="Math 2070" chapter="7" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=""><keywords slide="14" environ="slide" chapter="7" course="Math 2070"/>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Claim" wbtag="claim" num="12" md5="3db3b3b565ba9ccf73513c010f0852a8" course="Math 2070" chapter="7" slide="14" item="7.12">
In a ring $R$, there is a unique additive identity element
and a unique multiplicative identity element.
</statement>
<substatement environment="substatement" chapter_type="Week" type="Proof" wbtag="proof" md5="7898e16c1a978cf07b406aeda181188e" course="Math 2070" chapter="7" slide="14" of="3db3b3b565ba9ccf73513c010f0852a8">
<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
Suppose there is an element $0' \in R$ such that $0' + r = r$ for all $r \in R$, then
in particular $0' + 0 = 0$.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="collapse">
Since $0$ is an additive identity, we have $0' + 0 = 0'$.
So, $0' = 0$.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="collapse">
Suppose there is an element $1' \in R$ such that $1'r = r$ or all $r \in R$, 
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="collapse">
then in particular $1' \cdot 1 = 1$.  
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="collapse">
But $1' \cdot 1 = 1'$ since $1$ is a multiplicative identity element, so $1' = 1$.
<qed environment="newcol" chapter_type=""/>
</collapse></collapse></collapse></collapse></newcol>
</substatement>
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment=""/>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Exercise" wbtag="ex" num="13" md5="4362df2060aa5a9465ae569bbf3abfa1" course="Math 2070" chapter="7" slide="14" item="7.13">
<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
Prove that:
For any $r$ in a ring $R$, its additive inverse $-r$ is unique.
That is, if $r + r' = r + r'' = 0$, then $r' = r''$.
</newcol>
</statement>
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment=""/>
</slide>
        <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s15" slide="15" course="Math 2070" chapter="7" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=""><keywords slide="15" environ="slide" chapter="7" course="Math 2070"/>
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment=""/>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Example" wbtag="eg" num="14" md5="3e41d6dd3f6db83ff4917f820c2dd20b" course="Math 2070" chapter="7" slide="15" item="7.14">
The following sets, equipped with the usual operations of addition and multiplication,
are rings:
<col_ol environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_ol">
<col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
$\mathbb{Z}$, $\mathbb{Q}$, $\mathbb{R}$
</col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
$\mathbb{Z}[x]$, $\mathbb{Q}[x]$, $\mathbb{R}[x]$
(Polynomials with integer, rational, real coefficients, respectively.)
</col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
\[
\begin{split}
\mathbb{Q}[\sqrt{2}] &amp;=
\{\sum_{k = 0}^n a_k(\sqrt{2})^k | a_k \in \mathbb{Q}, n \in \mathbb{N}\}\\
&amp;= \{a + b\sqrt{2} | a, b \in \mathbb{Q}\}.
\end{split}
\]
</col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
For a fixed $n$, the set of $n\times n$ matrices with integer coefficients.
</col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
$C[0, 1] = \{f : [0, 1]\rightarrow \mathbb{R}\; |\; f \text{ is continuous.}\}$
</col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
$M_n(\mathbb{R})$,
the set of $n \times n$ real matrices, $n \in \mathbb{N}$.
</col_li></col_ol>
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="statement"/>
The following sets, under the usual operations of addition and multiplication, are not rings:
<col_ol environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_ol">
<col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
$\mathbb{N}$, no additive identity element, i.e. no 0.
</col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
$\mathbb{N}\cup\{0\}$, nonzero elements have no additive inverses.
</col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
$\GL(n, \mathbb{R})$,
the set of $n \times n$ invertible real matrices, $n \in \mathbb{N}$.
</col_li></col_ol>
</statement>
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment=""/>
</slide>
        <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s16" slide="16" course="Math 2070" chapter="7" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=""><keywords slide="16" environ="slide" chapter="7" course="Math 2070"/>
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment=""/>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Claim" wbtag="claim" num="15" md5="06c93e407cb78d275e72438b2177a1dd" course="Math 2070" chapter="7" slide="16" item="7.15">
For all elements $r$ in a ring $R$, we have $0r = r0 = 0$.
</statement>
<substatement environment="substatement" chapter_type="Week" type="Proof" wbtag="proof" md5="1f8a1cb45717ede2d17734b9c60b3784" course="Math 2070" chapter="7" slide="16" of="06c93e407cb78d275e72438b2177a1dd">
<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
By distributativity,
\[
0r = (0 + 0)r = 0r + 0r.
\]
<collapse environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="collapse">
Adding $-0r$ (additive inverse of $0r$) to both sides, we have:
\[
0 = (0r + 0r) + (-0r) = 0r + (0r + (-0r)) = 0r + 0 = 0r.
\]
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="collapse">
The proof of $r0 = 0$ is similar and we leave it as an <xh:strong xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol">exercise</xh:strong>.
<qed environment="newcol" chapter_type=""/>
</collapse></collapse></newcol>
</substatement>
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment=""/>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Claim" wbtag="claim" num="16" md5="ae67e49b63f437688b9241a878c3d85f" course="Math 2070" chapter="7" slide="16" item="7.16">
<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
For all elements $r$ in a ring, we have $(-1)(-r) = (-r)(-1)= r$.
</newcol></statement>
<substatement environment="substatement" chapter_type="Week" type="Proof" wbtag="proof" md5="6fdd0fa7d2c0fb732519b938c066c8dd" course="Math 2070" chapter="7" slide="16" of="ae67e49b63f437688b9241a878c3d85f">
<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
We have:
\[
0 = 0(-r) = (1 + (-1))(-r) = -r + (-1)(-r).
\]
<collapse environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="collapse">
Adding $r$ to both sides, we obtain
\[
r = r + (-r + (-1)(-r)) = (r + -r) + (-1)(-r) = (-1)(-r).
\]
<collapse environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="collapse">
We leave it as an <xh:strong xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol">exercise</xh:strong> to show that $(-r)(-1) = r$.
<qed environment="newcol" chapter_type=""/>
</collapse></collapse></newcol>
</substatement>
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment=""/>
</slide>
        <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s17" slide="17" course="Math 2070" chapter="7" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=""><keywords slide="17" environ="slide" chapter="7" course="Math 2070"><keyword chapter="7" slide="17">zero ring</keyword></keywords>
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment=""/>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Exercise" wbtag="ex" num="17" md5="97fcac3949c90d57ee7ba8b8f664bd28" course="Math 2070" chapter="7" slide="17" item="7.17">
Show that:
For all $r$ in a ring $R$, we have:
\[
(-1) r = r(-1) = -r.
\]
</statement>
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment=""/>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Exercise" wbtag="ex" num="18" md5="1c2e2ec38e571aff1c68a3aef3bbf546" course="Math 2070" chapter="7" slide="17" item="7.18">
<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
Show that:
If $R$ is a ring in which $1 = 0$, then $R = \{0\}$.  That is, it has only one element.
<xh:p xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol"/>
(We call such an $R$ the <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol">zero ring</xh:b>.)
</newcol>
</statement>
